Title : Laura Pritchett
Text : {{Use mdy dates|date=May 2014}}
'''Laura Pritchett''' (born February 16, 1971) is an American writer. Pritchett is the author of five literary novels and  one book of nonfiction. Her work is rooted in the American West and has been  significantly influenced by her native Colorado. Both her fiction and   nonfiction often focus on issues of ecology,  conservation, climate change, and social justice issues. She has been awarded  the PEN USA Award for Fiction, the High Plains Literary Award, the Milkweed  National Fiction Prize, the WILLA Fiction Award, and others. She is the editor  of three anthologies, all on environmental topics, and writes regularly for  magazines.

==Life==
Laura Pritchett grew up on a small [[ranch]] in northern [[Colorado]]. She received her BA and MA in [[English studies|English]] at [[Colorado State University]], and has a PhD in English with an emphasis in [[American literature#Contemporary American literature|Contemporary American Literature]] and Creative Writing from [[Purdue University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lib.colostate.edu/develop/events/2006/toc/pritchett.html|title=Laura Pritchett|author=Gregory Vogl|publisher=Lib.colostate.edu|accessdate=January 9, 2015}}</ref> She teaches for writing programs around the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lighthousewriters.org/person/facdetail/person/173/name/laura_pritchett_phd/|title=Lighthouse Writers Workshop  - Laura Pritchett, PhD|publisher=Lighthousewriters.org|accessdate=January 9, 2015}}</ref> Pritchett also writes for several magazines, most often about environmental issues in the [[Western United States|American West]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thenormalschool.com/?page_id=144|title=The Normal People|publisher=Thenormalschool.com|accessdate=January 9, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.5280.com/tag/authors/laura-pritchett|title=Laura Pritchett|publisher=5280.com|accessdate=January 9, 2015}}</ref>

Her book, ''Stars Go Blue'', released by Counterpoint in 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://counterpointpress.com/products/stars-go-blue/|title=Stars Go Blue|work=Counterpoint Press|accessdate=January 9, 2015}}</ref> was heavily inspired by her father's struggle with [[Alzheimer's]] disease and the impact of his disease on her extended family.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fictionwritersreview.com/interview/grafting-experiences-like-hides-a-conversation-with-laura-pritchett/|title=Grafting Experiences like Hides: A Conversation with Laura Pritchett|work=Fiction Writers Review|accessdate=January 9, 2015}}</ref> The book had an enthusiastic critical reception, including starred reviews from [[Booklist]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.booklistonline.com/Stars-Go-Blue-Laura-Pritchett/pid=6547562|title=Stars Go Blue, by Laura  Pritchett - Booklist Online|publisher=Booklistonline.com|accessdate=January 9, 2015}}</ref> and [[Library Journal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bookverdict.com/viewlist.xqy?uri=961177436.xml|title=Library Journal: May 1, 2014 Starred Reviews - Bookverdict.com|publisher=Bookverdict.com|accessdate=January 9, 2015}}</ref>

It won the High Plains Literary Award and was a finalist for several others.

''Red Lightning'' was released in 2015, and traces the story of a young coyote who has been transporting individuals once they’re past the US-Mexico border. Her other novels include ''Sky Bridge'', released from Milkweed Editions in 2005, and ''Hell’s Bottom, Colorado'', released from the same press in 2001. This book won the PEN USA Award for Fiction and the Milkweed National Fiction Prize.

==Awards==
Milkweed National Fiction Prize, ''Hell’s Bottom, Colorado''<ref>http://milkweed.org/authors/laura-pritchett/</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ouray.colibraries.org/award-winning-books/milkweed-prize-winners.html|title=Milkweed Prize Winners|publisher=Ouray.colibraries.org|accessdate=January 9, 2015}}</ref><br>
PEN USA West Literary Award for Fiction, ''Hell’s Bottom, Colorado''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.penusa.org/hells-bottom-colorado|title=Hell's Bottom, Colorado|publisher=Penusa.org|accessdate=January 9, 2015}}</ref><br>
WILLA Literary Award for ''Sky Bridge''<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Womenwritingthewest.org|title=2006 WILLA Literary Award Winners and Finalists|format=PDF|url=http://www.womenwritingthewest.org/pdffiles/2011/willa/2006%20WILLA%20Winners-Finalists.pdf|accessdate=9 January 2015}}</ref><br>
Colorado Book Award, ''Home Land: Ranching and a West That Works'' (anthology)<ref>http://www.coloradohumanities.org/content/colorado-book-awards-history</ref>

